<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - PISTON AND
        ROD ASSEMBLY
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>PISTON AND ROD ASSEMBLY</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <para>Remove the following:</para>
            <para>Fuel injection lines (high pressure)</para>
            <para>Fuel leak-off lines (low pressure)</para>
            <para>Aneroid tube</para>
            <para>Valve cover/Intake manifold</para>
            <para>Turbocharger oil inlet and oil drain tubes</para>
            <para>Valve lever assembly</para>
            <para>Cylinder head assembly</para>
            <para>Vibration damper</para>
            <para>Oil pan</para>
            <para>Oil pick-up tube</para>
            <para>Refer to the appropriate title for detailed removal procedures.</para>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="5">
            <title>REMOVAL</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a razor knife, scrape the carbon ridge from the top of the cylinder sleeve. Refer
                    to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050602">6.2</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>THE CARBON RIDGE MUST BE REMOVED BEFORE REMOVING THE PISTON AND ROD ASSEMBLY. THIS REDUCES
                            THE CHANCE OF PISTON RING LAND DAMAGE DURING REMOVAL.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the connecting rod bolts using a socket and breaker-bar,
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050603">6.3</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the bolts by hand.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The bolts should turn out of the connecting rod freely. If binding exists, check thread
                            condition carefully.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the connecting rod cap and bearing insert. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050604">6.4</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050602" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg1721" filename="../figeg1/EG1721.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.2.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050603" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2407" filename="../figeg2/EG2407.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.3.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Connecting Rod Bolt (12)</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Connecting Rod Cap (6)</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Crankcase</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050604" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2408" filename="../figeg2/EG2408.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.4.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Connecting Rod Cap (6)</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Crankcase</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Crankshaft</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the piston and connecting rod assemblies as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Push the piston and rod assembly from the cylinder bore using a wood or plastic
                        handle. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050605">6.5</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Once the piston rings are free of cylinder bore, the assembly can be removed from
                        the top of the crankcase. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050606">6.6</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Rotate engine and remove all of the remaining pistons as outlined. Be sure to
                        replace each bearing cap on its respective connecting rod after removal of the piston from the
                        engine.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Identify the connecting rod and piston assemblies upon removal so they can be
                        reinstalled in their respective cylinder bores.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050605" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2409" filename="../figeg2/EG2409.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.5.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Connecting Rod</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Crankcase</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Hammer</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050606" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2368" filename="../figeg2/EG2368.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.6.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Connecting Rod/Piston Assembly</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Crankcase</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
